{
  "texts": [
    "Now take an x ′ as in (6.9) and consider any z ′ such that x ′ R α z ′.",
    "We claim that M, z ′ ⊩ ¬□ β p. So consider any z ⊑ z ′.",
    "By R-down, x ′ R α z ′ implies x ′ R α z, so by (6.9) there is a u with yR γ u and zR β u.",
    "Then since M, y ⊩ □ γ ¬p, yR γ u implies M, u ⊩ ¬p, which with zR β u implies M, z ⊮ □ β p. Since this there is a model M based on F and an x ∈ M such that M, x ⊮ □ δ ♢ γ p. Thus, there is a y ′ such that xR δ y ′ and M, y ′ ⊮ ♢ γ p, i.e., M, y ′ ⊮ ¬□ γ ¬p, so there is a y ⊑ y ′ such that M, y ⊩ □ γ ¬p.",
    "By R-down, xR δ y ′ implies xR δ y.Then by (6.10) there is a u with yR γ u and xR β u."
  ]
}